  abstract = {It is anticipated that the mobile and the higher end immersive technology equipment will be accelerated by the nearing 5G and Wi-Fi 6 respectively, and there is, however, no specific safety standard in the market. It is envisioned that immersive technologies (in terms of VR, AR and MR) will become the next paradigm of human-computer interaction and therefore the prolonged use of such equipment will become more commonplace, furthering the need for a holistic system safety standard. As it creates multisensory experiences between the real and virtual worlds, visually induced motion sickness (or cybersickness) due to excessive motion-to-photon latency, mismatch between interpupillary and interaxial distances, and the subsequent fall and collision injury, may occur. It typically comes in the form of head-mounted displays and is battery-powered in close vicinity of human body that necessitates onerous battery safety and thermal requirements. It can also cause biomechanical stress on the neck if unduly heavy.},
